# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: x509-certificates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] In cryptography, a **certificate revocation list** (**CRL**) is "a list of digital certificates that have been revoked by the issuing certificate authority (CA) before their scheduled expiration date and should no longer be trusted".
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Publicly trusted CAs in the Web PKI are required (including by the CA/Browser forum) to issue CRLs for their certificates, and they widely do.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Browsers and other relying parties might use CRLs, or might use alternate certificate revocation technologies (such as OCSP) or CRLSets (a dataset derived from CRLs) to check certificate revocation status.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Note that OCSP is falling out of favor due to privacy and performance concerns, resulting in a return to CRLs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Subscribers and other parties can also use ARI.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] A certificate is irreversibly revoked if, for example, it is discovered that the certificate authority (CA) had improperly issued a certificate, or if a private-key is thought to have been compromised.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Certificates may also be revoked for failure of the identified entity to adhere to policy requirements, such as publication of false documents, misrepresentation of software behaviour, or violation of any other policy specified by the CA operator or its customer.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] The most common reason for revocation is the user no longer being in sole possession of the private key (e.g., the token containing the private key has been lost or stolen).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] This reversible status can be used to note the temporary invalidity of the certificate (e.g., if the user is unsure if the private key has been lost).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] If, in this example, the private key was found and nobody had access to it, the status could be reinstated, and the certificate is valid again, thus removing the certificate from future CRLs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL is generated and published periodically, often at a defined interval.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL can also be published immediately after a certificate has been revoked.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] A CRL is issued by a CRL issuer, which is typically the CA which also issued the corresponding certificates, but could alternatively be some other trusted authority.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] All CRLs have a lifetime during which they are valid; this timeframe is often 24 hours or less.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] During a CRL's validity period, it may be consulted by a PKI-enabled application to verify a certificate prior to use.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] To prevent spoofing or denial-of-service attacks, CRLs usually carry a digital signature associated with the CA by which they are published.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] To validate a specific CRL prior to relying on it, the certificate of its corresponding CA is needed.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] The certificates for which a CRL should be maintained are often X.509/public key certificates, as this format is commonly used by PKI schemes.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Expiration dates are not a substitute for a CRL.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] While all expired certificates are considered invalid, not all unexpired certificates should be valid.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] CRLs or other certificate validation techniques are a necessary part of any properly operated PKI, as mistakes in certificate vetting and key management are expected to occur in real world operations.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] In a noteworthy example, a certificate for Microsoft was mistakenly issued to an unknown individual, who had successfully posed as Microsoft to the CA contracted to maintain the ActiveX 'publisher certificate' system (VeriSign).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Microsoft saw the need to patch their cryptography subsystem so it would check the status of certificates before trusting them.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] As a short-term fix, a patch was issued for the relevant Microsoft software (most importantly Windows) specifically listing the two certificates in question as "revoked".
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Best practices require that wherever and however certificate status is maintained, it must be checked whenever one wants to rely on a certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Failing this, a revoked certificate may be incorrectly accepted as valid.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] This means that to use a PKI effectively, one must have access to current CRLs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] This requirement of on-line validation negates one of the original major advantages of PKI over symmetric cryptography protocols, namely that the certificate is "self-authenticating".
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Symmetric systems such as Kerberos also depend on the existence of on-line services (a key distribution center in the case of Kerberos).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] The existence of a CRL implies the need for someone (or some organization) to enforce policy and revoke certificates deemed counter to operational policy.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] If a certificate is mistakenly revoked, significant problems can arise.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] As the certificate authority is tasked with enforcing the operational policy for issuing certificates, they typically are responsible for determining if and when revocation is appropriate by interpreting the operational policy.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] The necessity of consulting a CRL (or other certificate status service) prior to accepting a certificate raises a potential denial-of-service attack against the PKI.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] If acceptance of a certificate fails in the absence of an available valid CRL, then no operations depending upon certificate acceptance can take place.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] This issue exists for Kerberos systems as well, where failure to retrieve a current authentication token will prevent system access.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] An alternative to using CRLs is the certificate validation protocol known as Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] OCSP has the primary benefit of requiring less network bandwidth, enabling real-time and near real-time status checks for high volume or high-value operations.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] As of Firefox 28, Mozilla has announced they are deprecating CRL in favour of OCSP.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] CRL files may grow quite large over time e.g. in US government, for certain institution multiple megabytes.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] Therefore, incremental CRLs have been designed sometimes referred to as "delta CRLs".
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] However, only a few clients implement them.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-revocation-list] An *authority revocation list* (ARL) is a form of CRL containing revoked certificates issued to certificate authorities, contrary to CRLs which contain revoked end-entity certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] In public key infrastructure (PKI) systems, a **certificate signing request** (**CSR** or **certification request**) is a message sent from an applicant to a certificate authority of the public key infrastructure (PKI) in order to apply for a digital identity certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The CSR usually contains the public key for which the certificate should be issued, identifying information (such as a holder or domain name) and a proof of possession of the corresponding private key (typically in the form of a digital signature, which includes integrity protection).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The most common format for CSRs is the **PKCS #10** specification, first published in November 1993; others include the more capable Certificate Request Message Format (CRMF) and the SPKAC (Signed Public Key and Challenge) format generated by some web browsers.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Note that neither of the CSR formats authenticate the identity of the requester.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The proof of origin of the request must be achieved and verified by other means (typically using a certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME), otherwise the obtained certificate has no real security value.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The CSR contains information identifying the applicant (such as a distinguished name), the public key chosen by the applicant, and possibly further information.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] When using the PKCS #10 format, the request must be self-signed using the applicant's private key, which provides proof of possession (POP) of the private key but limits the use of this format to keys that can be used for (some form of) signing.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The CSR must be accompanied by a proof of origin (i.e., proof of identity of the applicant), which is required for security reasons by the certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The certificate authority may contact the applicant for further information.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Typical information required in a CSR (sample column from sample X.509 certificate).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Note that there are often alternatives for the Distinguished Names (DN), the preferred value is listed.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The CSR is typically sent to a Registration Authority (RA), which checks the CSR contents and authenticates the applicant.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] On success the CSR is forwarded to a Certificate Authority (CA), which produces the X.509 public-key certificate, digitally signing it using the CA private key, and sends the new certificate to the applicant.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] A certification request in PKCS #10 format consists of three main parts: the certification request information, a signature algorithm identifier, and a digital signature on the certification request information using the private key related to the public key being certified.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The signature constitutes a self-signature with the key pair of the applicant.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Due to the self-signature requirement, this format is applicable only to types of keys that support signing.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Yet there are variants of this format that do not include an actual signature, such as described in Appendix C.1 of RFC 5272 (CMS).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The first part contains as its most significant information the public key and the identity of the applicant.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The self-signature by the applicant provides a proof of possession (POP).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Checking the POP prevents an entity from requesting a bogus certificate of someone else's public key.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Thus the private key is required to produce a PKCS #10 CSR.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Yet note that the POP for the key pair by the subject entity does not provide any authentication of the subject entity.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The proof of origin for the request by the applicant must therefore be provided and checked by other means.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] Otherwise illegitimate certificates can be produced where the subject/holder information is wrong.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] CSR for personal ID certificates and signing certificates usually includes the email address of the ID holder or the name of organisation in case of business ID.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The attributes can contain required certificate extensions, a challenge-password to restrict revocations, as well as any additional information about the subject of the certificate, possibly including local or future types.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] The PKCS#10 standard defines syntax, semantics, and binary format for CSRs for use with X.509.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-signing-request] This was generated by supplying the base64 encoding into the command `openssl asn1parse -in *your_request.p10* -inform PEM -i` where PEM (Privacy-Enhanced Mail) is the encoding of the ASN.1 Distinguished Encoding Rules in base64.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency makes public all issued certificates in the form of a distributed ledger, giving website owners and auditors the ability to detect and expose inappropriately issued certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Work on Certificate Transparency first began in 2011 after the certificate authority DigiNotar became compromised and started issuing malicious certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Google engineers submitted a draft to the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) in 2012.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] This effort resulted in IETF RFC 6962, a standard defining a system of public logs to record all certificates issued by publicly trusted certificate authorities, allowing efficient identification of mistakenly or maliciously issued certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The certificate transparency system consists of a system of append-only certificate logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Logs are operated by many parties, including browser vendors and certificate authorities.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Certificates that support certificate transparency must include one or more *signed certificate timestamps* (SCTs), which is a promise from a log operator to include the certificate in their log within a *maximum merge delay* (MMD).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] At some point within the maximum merge delay, the log operator adds the certificate to their log.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Each entry in a log references the hash of a previous one, forming a Merkle tree.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The *signed tree head* (STH) references the current root of the Merkle tree.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The CA issues a special *precertificate*, a certificate which carries a poison extension signaling that it should not be accepted by user agents.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The CA sends the precertificate to logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Logs return corresponding SCTs to the CA.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The CA attaches SCTs collected from logs as an X.509 extension to the final certificate and provides it to the applicant.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Finally, the CA may decide to log the final certificate as well.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Let's Encrypt E1 CA, for example, logs both precertificates and final certificates (see CA crt.sh profile page under 'issued certificates' section), whereas Google GTS CA 2A1 does not (see crt.sh profile page).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Due to the large quantities of certificates issued with the Web PKI, certificate transparency logs can grow to contain many certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] This large quantity of certificates can cause strain on logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Temporal sharding is a method to reduce the strain on logs by sharding a log into multiple logs, and having each shard only accept precertificates and certificates with an expiration date in a particular time period (usually a calendar year).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Cloudflare's Nimbus series of logs was the first to use temporal sharding.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] One of the problems with digital certificate management is that fraudulent certificates take a long time to be spotted, reported and revoked.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] An issued certificate not logged using Certificate Transparency may never be spotted at all.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The main advantage with Certificate Transparency is the ability for cyber security teams to defend companies and organisations by monitoring for suspicious domains registering certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] The new certificates for these suspicious domains may have similar names to other legitimate domains and are designed to be used to support malicious activities such as phishing attacks.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency puts cyber security teams in control and enables them to issue domain take down orders for suspicious domains and allows them to apply cyber security controls on web proxies and email gateways for immediate protection.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Domain names that are used on internal networks and have certificates issued by certificate authorities become publicly searchable as their certificates are added to CT logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency depends on verifiable Certificate Transparency logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] A log appends new certificates to an ever-growing Merkle hash tree.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] A log may accept certificates that are not yet fully valid and certificates that have expired.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] There are two primary categories of monitors: log integrity monitors (also referred to as log verifiers or log auditors) and tracking monitors.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Some companies offering monitoring services collect data from all logs and provide paid services for domain tracking.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] For example, a domain owner can register for Cloudflare's services, which globally monitor all logs and send email updates whenever a certificate is issued for their domain, allowing them control over all certificates issued.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Large organizations can maintain their own monitors, which continuously scan for new certificate issued for their domains.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] If a certificate authority (CA) attempts to issue a "bad" certificate for one of these domains (intentionally or unintentionally), the monitor will quickly detect it.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Two popular APIs for research and tracking are Sectigo's crt.sh and Cloudflare MerkleTown.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] These tools facilitate the monitoring of certificate issuance and help organizations stay on top of the security of their domains.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] While there is an additional consideration of monitoring the monitors themselves, the likelihood of a significant impact on system performance or security due to misbehavior of a single monitor is low.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] This is because there are numerous log monitors, providing a layered approach to security and minimizing the risk of a single point of failure.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Apple and Google have separate log programs with distinct policies and lists of trusted logs.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Certificate Transparency logs maintain their own root stores and only accept certificates that chain back to the trusted roots.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] A number of misbehaving logs have been publishing inconsistent root stores in the past.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] A new structure for logs is based on dividing the Merkle Tree into tiles.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] This structure is expected to be faster, easier to operate, and to provide much smaller merge delays (the current Maximum Merge Delay is 24 hours).
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Chrome has updated its Certificate Transparency (CT) policy to accept SCTs from the new static-CT-API logs only if an SCT from an RFC 6962 log is also present, and it intends to complete the migration to static-CT-API CT logs by the end of 2025.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In 2011, a reseller of the certificate authority Comodo was attacked and the certificate authority DigiNotar was compromised, demonstrating existing flaws in the certificate authority ecosystem and prompting work on various mechanisms to prevent or monitor unauthorized certificate issuance.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Google employees Ben Laurie, Adam Langley and Emilia Kasper began work on an open source framework for detecting mis-issued certificates the same year.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In 2012, they submitted the first draft of the standard to IETF under the code-name "Sunlight".
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In March 2013, Google launched its first certificate transparency log.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In June 2013, RFC 6962 "Certificate Transparency" was published, based on the 2012 draft.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In September 2013, DigiCert became the first certificate authority to implement Certificate Transparency.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In 2015, Google Chrome began requiring Certificate Transparency for newly issued Extended Validation Certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] It began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates newly issued by Symantec from June 1, 2016, after they were found to have issued 187 certificates without the domain owners' knowledge.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Since April 2018, this requirement has been extended to all certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] On March 23, 2018, Cloudflare announced its own CT log named *Nimbus*.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In May 2019, certificate authority Let's Encrypt launched its own CT log called Oak.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Since February 2020, it is included in approved log lists and is usable by all publicly trusted certificate authorities.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In December 2021, RFC 9162 "Certificate Transparency Version 2.0" was published.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] Version 2.0 includes major changes to the required structure of the log certificate, as well as support for Ed25519 as a signature algorithm of SCTs and support for including certificate inclusion proofs with the SCT.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] However, it has not seen industry adoption and is considered dead on arrival.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In February 2022, Google published an update to their CT policy, which removes the requirement for certificates to include a SCT from their own CT log service, matching all the requirements for certificates to those previously published by Apple.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In February 2025, Mozilla Firefox desktop version 135 began requiring Certificate Transparency for all certificates issued by a certificate authority in Mozilla's Root CA Program.
[src:x509-certificates/certificate-transparency] In Certificate Transparency Version 2.0, a log must use one of the algorithms in the IANA registry "Signature Algorithms".
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] A **cipher suite** is a set of algorithms that help secure a network connection.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Suites typically use Transport Layer Security (TLS) or its deprecated predecessor Secure Socket Layer (SSL) as their protocol.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The set of algorithms that cipher suites usually contain include: a key exchange algorithm, a bulk encryption algorithm, and a message authentication code (MAC) algorithm.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The key exchange algorithm is used to exchange a key between two devices.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This key is used to encrypt and decrypt the messages being sent between two machines.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The bulk encryption algorithm is used to encrypt the data being sent.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The MAC algorithm provides data integrity checks to ensure that the data sent does not change in transit.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In addition, cipher suites can include signatures and an authentication algorithm to help authenticate the server and or client.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Overall, there are hundreds of different cipher suites that contain different combinations of these algorithms.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Some cipher suites offer better security than others.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] But with the adoption of TLS 1.3, only 5 cipher suites have been officially supported and defined.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The structure and use of the cipher suite concept are defined in the TLS standard document.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] TLS 1.2 is the most prevalent version of TLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The newest version of TLS (TLS 1.3) includes additional requirements to cipher suites.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Cipher suites defined for TLS 1.2 cannot be used in TLS 1.3, and vice versa, unless otherwise stated in their definition.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] A reference list of named cipher suites is provided in the TLS Cipher Suite Registry.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The use of ciphers has been a part of the Secure Socket Layer (SSL) transit protocol since its creation.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] SSL has been succeeded by TLS for most uses.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] However, the name *Cipher Suite* was not used in the original draft of SSL.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Instead the ability for a client and a server to choose from a small set of ciphers to secure their connection was called *Cipher-Choice.* It was not until SSL v3 (the last version of SSL) that the name *Cipher Suite* was used.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Every version of TLS since has used *Cipher Suite* in its standardization.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The concept and purpose of a *Cipher Suite* has not changed since the term was first coined.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] It has and still is used as a structure describing the algorithms that a machine supports in order for two machines to decide which algorithms to use to secure their connection.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] What has changed is the versions of the algorithms that are supported in the cipher suites.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Each version of TLS has added support for stronger versions of the algorithms and removed support for versions of the algorithms that have been identified as insecure.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] TLS 1.3 marks a change in how cipher suites are coordinated between machines.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The cipher suite chosen for two communicating machines to use is determined by the handshake process.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Modifications were done in TLS 1.3 to the handshake process to cut down on the number of messages needed to be sent.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This allows for less processing, less packet traffic and more efficiency compared to previous versions of TLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Each cipher suite has a unique name that is used to identify it and to describe the algorithmic contents of it.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Each segment in a cipher suite name stands for a different algorithm or protocol.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] defines the protocol that this cipher suite is for; it will usually be TLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] authentication mechanism during the handshake.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] type of encryption (cipher-block dependency and additional options).
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] which is used to authenticate a message.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] As of TLS 1.3 cipher suite names no longer include a certificate type (RSA) or key exchange mechanism (ECDHE), as these are negotiated separately in the new version.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] To use cipher suites, the client and the server must agree on the specific cipher suite that is going to be used in exchanging messages.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Both the client and the server must support the agreed upon cipher suite.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If the client and server do not agree on a cipher suite, no connection will be made.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This selection process occurs during the TLS Handshake Protocol.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] TLS 1.3 includes a TLS Handshake Protocol that differs compared to past and the current version of TLS/SSL.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] After coordinating which cipher suite to use, the server and the client still have the ability to change the coordinated ciphers by using the *ChangeCipherSpec* protocol in the current handshake or in a new handshake.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] To test which TLS ciphers a server supports, an SSL/TLS Scanner may be used.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This client starts the process by sending a *clientHello* message to the server that includes the version of TLS being used and a cipher suites list in the order of the client's preference.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In response, the server sends a *serverHello* message that includes the chosen cipher suite and the session ID.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Next the server sends a digital certificate to verify its identity to the client.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The server may also request a client's digital certification if needed.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If the client and server are not using pre-shared keys, the client then sends an encrypted message to the server that enables the client and the server to compute which secret key will be used during exchanges.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If the *prefer server cipher* bit of *serverHello* message is set to true, the negotiated cipher suite is preferred on the cipher suites list of *serverHello* message; otherwise, the negotiated cipher suite is preferred on the cipher suites list of *clientHello* message.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] After successfully verifying the authentication of the server and, if needed, exchanging the secret key, the client sends a *finished* message to signal that it is done with the handshake process.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] After receiving this message, the server sends a *finished* message that confirms that the handshake is complete.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Now the client and the server are in agreement on which cipher suite to use to communicate with each other.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If two machines are corresponding over TLS 1.3, they coordinate which cipher suite to use by using the TLS 1.3 Handshake Protocol.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The handshake in TLS 1.3 was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] First the client sends a *clientHello* message to the server that contains a list of supported ciphers in order of the client's preference and makes a guess on what key algorithm is being used so that it can send a secret key to share if needed.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] By making a guess on what key algorithm that is being used it eliminates a round trip.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] After receiving the *clientHello*, the server sends a *serverHello* with its key, a certificate, the chosen cipher suite and the *finished* message.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] After the client receives the server's *finished* message it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In TLS 1.3, many legacy algorithms that were supported in early versions of TLS have been dropped in an effort to make the protocol more secure.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In addition, all encryption and authentication algorithms are combined in the authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD) encryption algorithm.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Also a hash algorithm must now be used in HMAC-based key derivation (HKDF).
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] All non-AEAD ciphers have been removed due to possible weaknesses or vulnerabilities and ciphers must use an ephemeral key exchange algorithm so that new key pairs are generated for every exchange.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is based on TLS, but is specifically used for UDP connections instead of TCP connections.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Since DTLS is based on TLS it is able to use a majority of the cipher suites described for TLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] There are special cases that must be considered when using TLS cipher suites with DTLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] DTLS does not support the stream cipher RC4 which means no TLS cipher suite using RC4 can be used with DTLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] To determine if a TLS cipher suite is compatible with DTLS looking at its name will not help.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Each TLS cipher suite will still include the TLS identifier space in its name. e.g.: *TLS_ECDHE_RSA_WITH_AES_128_GCM_SHA256*.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Instead, all TLS parameter registries now include the flag DTLS-OK to signal if a cipher suite supports DTLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] A cipher suite is as secure as the algorithms that it contains.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If the version of encryption or authentication algorithm in a cipher suite have known vulnerabilities the cipher suite and TLS connection may then be vulnerable.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Therefore, a common attack against TLS and cipher suites is known as a downgrade attack.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] A downgrade in TLS occurs when a modern client connects to legacy servers that are using older versions of TLS or SSL.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] When initiating a handshake, the modern client will offer the highest protocol that it supports.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If the connection fails, it will automatically retry again with a lower protocol such as TLS 1.0 or SSL 3.0 until the handshake is successful with the server.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The purpose of downgrading is so that new versions of TLS are compatible with older versions.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] However, it is possible for an adversary to take advantage of this feature and make it so that a client will automatically downgrade to a version of TLS or SSL that supports cipher suites with algorithms that are known for weak security and vulnerabilities.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This has resulted in attacks such as POODLE.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] One way to avoid this security flaw is to disable the ability of a server or client to be able to downgrade to SSL 3.0.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The shortcoming with this fix is that some legacy hardware cannot be accessed by newer hardware.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] If SSL 3.0 support is needed for legacy hardware, there is an approved TLS_FALLBACK_SCSV cipher suite which verifies that downgrades are not triggered for malicious intentions.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Encryption, key exchange and authentication algorithms usually require a large amount of processing power and memory.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] To provide security to constrained devices with limited processing power, memory, and battery life such as those powering the Internet of things there are specifically chosen cipher suites.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Each of these cipher suites has been implemented to run on devices with constraints in processing power and memory.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] They are both implemented in the open-sourced project TinyDTLS.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] The reason that they are able to work on these constrained devices is because they can be implemented in a light-weight fashion.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] Implementations of the pre-shared key cipher suite used only 1889 bytes of RAM and 38266 of flash ROM which is very resource-conscious compared to most encryption and security algorithms.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] This low memory usage is due to these cipher suites using proven efficient algorithms that are secure, but maybe not as secure as more resource-required algorithms; exp: Using 128 bit encryption vs 256 bit encryption.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In addition they use pre-shared key or **raw** public key which requires less memory space and processing power compared to using traditional public key infrastructure (PKIX).
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] In programming, a cipher suite is referred to in both plural and non-plural forms.
[src:x509-certificates/cipher-suite] a list of the cryptographic options supported by the client.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] An **Extended Validation (EV) Certificate** is a certificate conforming to X.509 that proves the legal entity of the owner and is signed by a certificate authority key that can issue EV certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] EV certificates can be used in the same manner as any other X.509 certificates, including securing web communications with HTTPS and signing software and documents.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Unlike domain-validated certificates and organization-validation certificates, EV certificates can be issued only by a subset of certificate authorities (CAs) and require verification of the requesting entity's legal identity before certificate issuance.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] As of February 2021, all major web browsers (Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, Microsoft Edge and Apple Safari) have menus which show the EV status of the certificate and the verified legal identity of EV certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Mobile browsers typically display EV certificates the same way they do Domain Validation (DV) and Organization Validation (OV) certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Of the ten most popular websites online, none use EV certificates and the trend is away from their usage.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] For software, the verified legal identity is displayed to the user by the operating system (e.g., Microsoft Windows) before proceeding with the installation.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Extended Validation certificates are stored in a file format specified by and typically use the same encryption as organization-validated certificates and domain-validated certificates, so they are compatible with most server and user agent software.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The criteria for issuing EV certificates are defined by the *Guidelines for Extended Validation* established by the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] To issue an extended validation certificate, a CA requires verification of the requesting entity's identity and its operational status with its control over domain name and hosting server.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] In 2005 Melih Abdulhayoglu, CEO of the Comodo Group (*currently known as Xcitium*), convened the first meeting of the organization that became the CA/Browser Forum, hoping to improve standards for issuing SSL/TLS certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] On June 12, 2007, the CA/Browser Forum officially ratified the first version of the Extended Validation (EV) SSL Guidelines, which took effect immediately.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The formal approval successfully brought to a close more than two years of effort and provided the infrastructure for trusted website identity on the Internet.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Then, in April 2008, the forum announced version 1.1 of the guidelines, building on the practical experience of its member CAs and relying-party application software suppliers gained in the months since the first version was approved for use.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Most major browsers created special user interface indicators for pages loaded via HTTPS secured by an EV certificate soon after the creation of the standard.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] This includes Google Chrome 1.0, Internet Explorer 7.0, Firefox 3, Safari 3.2, Opera 9.5.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Furthermore, some mobile browsers, including Safari for iOS, Windows Phone, Firefox for Android, Chrome for Android, and iOS, added such UI indicators.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Usually, browsers with EV support display the validated identity—usually a combination of organization name and jurisdiction—contained in the EV certificate's 'subject' field.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] By clicking on the lock symbol, the user can obtain more information about the certificate, including the name of the certificate authority that issued the EV certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] In May 2018, Google announced plans to redesign user interfaces of Google Chrome to remove emphasis for EV certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Chrome 77, released in 2019, removed the EV certificate indication from the omnibox, but EV certificate status can be viewed by clicking on lock icon and then checking for legal entity name listed as "issued to" under "certificate".
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Firefox 70 removed the distinction in the omnibox or URL bar (EV and DV certificates are displayed similarly with just a lock icon), but the details about certificate EV status are accessible in the more detailed view that opens after clicking on the lock icon.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Apple Safari on iOS 12 and MacOS Mojave (released in September 2018) removed the visual distinction of EV status.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] With the exception of Extended Validation Certificates for .onion domains, it is otherwise not possible to get a wildcard Extended Validation Certificate – instead, all fully qualified domain names must be included in the certificate and inspected by the certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] EV certificates are standard X.509 digital certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The primary way to identify an EV certificate is by referencing the Certificate Policies (CP) extension field.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Each EV certificate's CP object identifier (OID) field identifies an EV certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Other EV OIDs may be documented in the issuer's Certification Practice Statement.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] As with root certificate authorities in general, browsers may not recognize all issuers.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The criteria for issuing Extended Validation certificates do not require issuing certificate authorities to immediately support Online Certificate Status Protocol for revocation checking.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] However, the requirement for a timely response to revocation checks by the browser has prompted most certificate authorities that had not previously done so to implement OCSP support.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Section 26-A of the issuing criteria requires CAs to support OCSP checking for all certificates issued after Dec.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The legal entity names are not unique, therefore an attacker who wants to impersonate an entity might incorporate a different business with the same name (but, e.g., in a different state or country) and obtain a valid certificate for it, but then use the certificate to impersonate the original site.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] In one demonstration, a researcher incorporated a business called "Stripe, Inc." in Kentucky and showed that browsers display it similarly to how they display certificate of payment processor "Stripe, Inc." incorporated in Delaware.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Researcher claimed the demonstration setup took about an hour of his time, US$100 in legal costs and US$77 for the certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Also, he noted that "with enough mouse clicks, [user] may be able to [view] the city and state [where entity is incorporated], but neither of these are helpful to a typical user, and they will likely just blindly trust the [EV certificate] indicator".
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Since EV certificates are being promoted and reported as a mark of a trustworthy website, some small business owners have voiced concerns that EV certificates give undue advantage to large businesses.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] The published drafts of the EV Guidelines excluded unincorporated business entities, and early media reports focused on that issue.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] Version 1.0 of the EV Guidelines was revised to embrace unincorporated associations as long as they were registered with a recognized agency, greatly expanding the number of organizations that qualified for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] In 2006, researchers at Stanford University and Microsoft Research conducted a usability study of the EV display in Internet Explorer 7.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] While proponents of EV certificates claim they help against phishing attacks, security expert Peter Gutmann states the new class of certificates restore a CA's profits which were eroded due to the race to the bottom that occurred among issuers in the industry.
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] According to Peter Gutmann, EV certificates are not effective against phishing because EV certificates are "not fixing any problem that the phishers are exploiting".
[src:x509-certificates/extended-validation-certificate] He suggests that the big commercial CAs have introduced EV certificates to return the old high prices.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In cryptography, a **public-key certificate**, also known as a **digital certificate** or **identity certificate**, is an electronic document used to prove the valid attribution of a public key to the identity of its holder.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The certificate includes the public key and information about it, information about the identity of its owner (called the subject), and the digital signature of an entity that has verified the certificate's contents (called the issuer).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] If the party examining the certificate trusts the issuer and finds the signature to be a valid signature of that issuer, then it can use the included public key to interact securely with the certificate's subject.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In email encryption, code signing, and e-signature systems, a certificate's subject is typically a person or organization.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] However, in Transport Layer Security (TLS) a certificate's subject is typically a computer or other device, though TLS certificates may identify organizations or individuals in addition to their core role in identifying devices.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] TLS, sometimes called by its older name Secure Sockets Layer (SSL), is notable for being a part of HTTPS, a protocol for securely browsing the web.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In a typical public-key infrastructure (PKI) scheme, the certificate issuer is a certificate authority (CA), usually a company that charges customers a fee to issue certificates for them.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] By contrast, in a web of trust scheme, individuals sign each other's keys directly, in a format that performs a similar function to a public-key certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate is typically requested from a PKI using a CSR, which needs to be transferred using a secure certificate enrollment protocol such as CMP, EST, or ACME.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The parties involved in the enrollment process must verify the authenticity, integrity, and authorization of the CSR, for which the certificate issuer bears the main responsibility.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In case of key compromise or other situations that may lead to unauthorized use, a certificate may need to be revoked.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The general format for public-key and attribute certificates is defined by X.509.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For public-key certificates, the format has been profiled by the IETF for Internet-related use cases, such as Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A digital certificate system provides a chain of trust, meaning most certificates can be validated against parent certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The chain starts with a **root certificate**, which serves as a trust anchor (a.k.a. root of trust).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This certificate is self-signed (see below) and has no parent.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The issuing certificate authority uses other methods to safeguard and validate this certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] An **intermediate certificate** has a purpose similar to that of the root certificate – its only use is to sign other certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] However, an intermediate certificate is not self-signed.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A root certificate or another intermediate certificate needs to sign it.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] An **end-entity certificate**, or **leaf certificate**, is any certificate that cannot sign other certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For instance, TLS/SSL server and client certificates, email certificates, code signing certificates, and qualified certificates are all end-entity certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol – as well as its outdated predecessor, the Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) protocol – ensures that the communication between a client computer and a server is secure.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The protocol requires the server to present a digital certificate, proving that it is the intended destination.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A trusted certificate authority has signed the certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The *Subject* field of the certificate must identify the primary hostname of the server as the *Common Name*.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This means that the name listed in the certificate should exactly match the domain name users connect to (for example, `www.example.com`), ensuring that the certificate is valid for that specific hostname.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The hostname must be publicly accessible, not using private addresses or reserved domains.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be valid for multiple hostnames (e.g., a domain and its subdomains).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Such certificates are commonly called *Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates* or *Unified Communications Certificates (UCC)*.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] These certificates contain the Subject Alternative Name field, though many CAs also put them into the *Subject Common Name* field for backward compatibility.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] If some of the hostnames contain an asterisk (*), a certificate may also be called a wildcard certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Once the certification path validation is successful, the client can establish an encrypted connection with the server.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Internet-facing servers, such as public Web servers, must obtain their certificates from a trusted, public certificate authority (CA).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Client certificates authenticate the client connecting to a TLS service, for instance to provide access control.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Because most services provide access to individuals, rather than devices, most client certificates contain an email address or personal name rather than a hostname.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In addition, the certificate authority that issues the client certificate is usually the service provider to which client connects because it is the provider that needs to perform authentication.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] While most web browsers support client certificates, the most common form of authentication on the Internet is a username and password pair.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Client certificates are more common in virtual private networks (VPN) and Remote Desktop Services, where they authenticate devices.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In accordance with the S/MIME protocol, email certificates can both establish the message integrity and encrypt messages.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] To establish encrypted email communication, the communicating parties must have their digital certificates in advance.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Each must send the other one digitally signed email and opt to import the sender's certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Some publicly trusted certificate authorities provide email certificates, but more commonly S/MIME is used when communicating within a given organization, and that organization runs its own CA, which is trusted by participants in that email system.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A self-signed certificate is a certificate with a subject that matches its issuer, and a signature that can be verified by its own public key.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Although this type of certificate is worthless for establishing remote trust between unacquainted parties, it has full trust value when the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] As discussed above (in § Chain of trust), a root certificate is a self-signed certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The certificate authority, which is the sole user of the certificate, uses other means to validate and safeguard it.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Another example is the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows, which issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of the encrypting user, and uses it to transparently decrypt data on the fly.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Subject Alternative Name (SAN) certificates are an extension to X.509 that allows various values to be associated with a security certificate using a `subjectAltName` field.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] These values are called *Subject Alternative Names* (SANs).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] As of May 2000, Subject Alternative Names are the preferred method of adding DNS names to certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The previous method of putting DNS names in the `commonName` field is now deprecated.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Google Chrome version 58 (March 2017) removed support for checking the `commonName` field at all, instead only looking at the SANs.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] As shown in the picture of Wikimedia's section on the right, the SAN field can contain wildcards.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Not all vendors support or endorse mixing wildcards into SAN certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A public-key certificate which uses an asterisk `*` (the *wildcard*) in the domain name portion of it subject is called a Wildcard certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Through the use of `*`, a single certificate may be used for multiple sub-domains.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] It is commonly used for transport layer security in computer networking.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Instead of getting separate certificates for subdomains, you can use a single certificate for all main domains and subdomains and reduce cost.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Note possible exceptions by CAs, for example wildcard-plus cert by DigiCert contains an automatic "Plus" property for the naked domain `example.com`.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Only a single level of subdomain matching is supported.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] It is not possible to get a wildcard for an Extended Validation Certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A workaround could be to add every virtual host name in the Subject Alternative Name (SAN) extension, the major problem being that the certificate needs to be reissued whenever a new virtual server is added.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Wildcards can be added as domains in multi-domain certificates or Unified Communications Certificates (UCC).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In addition, wildcards themselves can have `subjectAltName` extensions, including other wildcards.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For example, the wildcard certificate `*.wikipedia.org` has `*.m.wikimedia.org` as a Subject Alternative Name.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Thus it secures `www.wikipedia.org` as well as the completely different website name `meta.m.wikimedia.org`.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] RFC 6125 argues against wildcard certificates on security grounds, in particular "partial wildcards".
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The wildcard applies only to one level of the domain name.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] However, use of "partial-wildcard" certs is not recommended.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] As of 2011, partial wildcard support is optional, and is explicitly disallowed in SubjectAltName headers that are required for multi-name certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] All major browsers have deliberately **removed** support for partial-wildcard certificates; they will result in a "SSL_ERROR_BAD_CERT_DOMAIN" error.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Similarly, it is typical for standard libraries in programming languages to not support "partial-wildcard" certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For example, any "partial-wildcard" certificate will not work with the latest versions of both Python and Go.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A cert with multiple wildcards in a name is not allowed.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A cert with `*` plus a top-level domain is not allowed.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] International domain names encoded in ASCII (A-label) are labels that are ASCII-encoded and begin with `xn--`.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] URLs with international labels cannot contain wildcards.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] These are some of the most common fields in certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Most certificates contain a number of fields not listed here.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Note that in terms of a certificate's X.509 representation, a certificate is not "flat" but contains these fields nested in various structures within the certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This is an example of a decoded SSL/TLS certificate retrieved from SSL.com's website.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The issuer's common name (CN) is shown as `SSL.com EV SSL Intermediate CA RSA R3`, identifying this as an Extended Validation (EV) certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Validated information about the website's owner (SSL Corp) is located in the `Subject` field.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Subject Alternative Name` field contains a list of domain names covered by the certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The `X509v3 Extended Key Usage` and `X509v3 Key Usage` fields show all appropriate uses.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In the European Union, (advanced) electronic signatures on legal documents are commonly performed using digital signatures with accompanying identity certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] However, only qualified electronic signatures (which require using a qualified trust service provider and signature creation device) are given the same power as a physical signature.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In the X.509 trust model, a certificate authority (CA) is responsible for signing certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] These certificates act as an introduction between two parties, which means that a CA acts as a trusted third party.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A CA processes requests from people or organizations requesting certificates (called subscribers), verifies the information, and potentially signs an end-entity certificate based on that information.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] To perform this role effectively, a CA needs to have one or more broadly trusted root certificates or intermediate certificates and the corresponding private keys.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] CAs may achieve this broad trust by having their root certificates included in popular software, or by obtaining a cross-signature from another CA delegating trust.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Other CAs are trusted within a relatively small community, like a business, and are distributed by other mechanisms like Windows Group Policy.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Certificate authorities are also responsible for maintaining up-to-date revocation information about certificates they have issued, indicating whether certificates are still valid.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] They provide this information through Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP) and/or Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Some of the larger certificate authorities in the market include IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Some major software contain a list of certificate authorities that are trusted by default.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This makes it easier for end-users to validate certificates, and easier for people or organizations that request certificates to know which certificate authorities can issue a certificate that will be broadly trusted.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This is particularly important in HTTPS, where a web site operator generally wants to get a certificate that is trusted by nearly all potential visitors to their web site.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The policies and processes a provider uses to decide which certificate authorities their software should trust are called root programs.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Browsers other than Firefox generally use the operating system's facilities to decide which certificate authorities are trusted.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] So, for instance, Chrome on Windows trusts the certificate authorities included in the Microsoft Root Program, while on macOS or iOS, Chrome trusts the certificate authorities in the Apple Root Program.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Edge and Safari use their respective operating system trust stores as well, but each is only available on a single OS.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Firefox uses the Mozilla Root Program trust store on all platforms.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The Mozilla Root Program is operated publicly, and its certificate list is part of the open source Firefox web browser, so it is broadly used outside Firefox.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For instance, while there is no common Linux Root Program, many Linux distributions, like Debian, include a package that periodically copies the contents of the Firefox trust list, which is then used by applications.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Root programs generally provide a set of valid purposes with the certificates they include.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For instance, some CAs may be considered trusted for issuing TLS server certificates, but not for code signing certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This is indicated with a set of trust bits in a root certificate storage system.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate may be revoked before it expires, which signals that it is no longer valid.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Without revocation, an attacker would be able to exploit such a compromised or misissued certificate until expiry.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Hence, revocation is an important part of a public key infrastructure.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Revocation is performed by the issuing certificate authority, which produces a cryptographically authenticated statement of revocation.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For distributing revocation information to clients, timeliness of the discovery of revocation (and hence the window for an attacker to exploit a compromised certificate) trades off against resource usage in querying revocation statuses and privacy concerns.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] If revocation information is unavailable (either due to accident or an attack), clients must decide whether to *fail-hard* and treat a certificate as if it is revoked (and so degrade availability) or to *fail-soft* and treat it as unrevoked (and allow attackers to sidestep revocation).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Due to the cost of revocation checks and the availability impact from potentially-unreliable remote services, Web browsers limit the revocation checks they will perform, and will fail-soft where they do.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Certificate revocation lists are too bandwidth-costly for routine use, and the Online Certificate Status Protocol presents connection latency and privacy issues.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Other schemes have been proposed but have not yet been successfully deployed to enable fail-hard checking.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The most common use of certificates is for HTTPS-based web sites.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A web browser validates that an HTTPS web server is authentic, so that the user can feel secure that his/her interaction with the web site has no eavesdroppers and that the web site is who it claims to be.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This security is important for electronic commerce.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In practice, a web site operator obtains a certificate by applying to a certificate authority with a certificate signing request.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The certificate request is an electronic document that contains the web site name, company information and the public key.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The certificate provider signs the request, thus producing a public certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] During web browsing, this public certificate is served to any web browser that connects to the web site and proves to the web browser that the provider believes it has issued a certificate to the owner of the web site.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Further, the relationship between the purchaser of the certificate, the operator of the web site, and the generator of the web site content may be tenuous and is not guaranteed.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] At best, the certificate guarantees uniqueness of the web site, provided that the web site itself has not been compromised (hacked) or the certificate issuing process subverted.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider can opt to issue three types of certificates, each requiring its own degree of vetting rigor.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In order of increasing rigor (and naturally, cost) they are: Domain Validation, Organization Validation and Extended Validation.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] These rigors are loosely agreed upon by voluntary participants in the CA/Browser Forum.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue a domain-validated (DV) certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can demonstrate one vetting criterion: the right to administratively manage the affected DNS domain(s).
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider will issue an organization validation (OV) class certificate to a purchaser if the purchaser can meet two criteria: the right to administratively manage the domain name in question, and perhaps, the organization's actual existence as a legal entity.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A certificate provider publishes its OV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] To acquire an Extended Validation (EV) certificate, the purchaser must persuade the certificate provider of its legal identity, including manual verification checks by a human.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] As with OV certificates, a certificate provider publishes its EV vetting criteria through its certificate policy.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Until 2019, major browsers such as Chrome and Firefox generally offered users a visual indication of the legal identity when a site presented an EV certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This was done by showing the legal name before the domain, and a bright green color to highlight the change.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Most browsers deprecated this feature providing no visual difference to the user on the type of certificate used.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This change followed security concerns raised by forensic experts and successful attempts to purchase EV certificates to impersonate famous organizations, proving the inefficiency of these visual indicators and highlighting potential abuses.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] A web browser will give no warning to the user if a web site suddenly presents a different certificate, even if that certificate has a lower number of key bits, even if it has a different provider, and even if the previous certificate had an expiry date far into the future.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Where certificate providers are under the jurisdiction of governments, those governments may have the freedom to order the provider to generate any certificate, such as for the purposes of law enforcement.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Subsidiary wholesale certificate providers also have the freedom to generate any certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] All web browsers come with an extensive built-in list of trusted root certificates, many of which are controlled by organizations that may be unfamiliar to the user.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] Each of these organizations is free to issue any certificate for any web site and have the guarantee that web browsers that include its root certificates will accept it as genuine.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In this instance, end users must rely on the developer of the browser software to manage its built-in list of certificates and on the certificate providers to behave correctly and to inform the browser developer of problematic certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] While uncommon, there have been incidents in which fraudulent certificates have been issued: in some cases, the browsers have detected the fraud; in others, some time passed before browser developers removed these certificates from their software.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] The list of built-in certificates is also not limited to those provided by the browser developer: users (and to a degree applications) are free to extend the list for special purposes such as for company intranets.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This means that if someone gains access to a machine and can install a new root certificate in the browser, that browser will recognize websites that use the inserted certificate as legitimate.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] For provable security, this reliance on something external to the system has the consequence that any public-key certification scheme has to rely on some special setup assumption, such as the existence of a certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] In spite of the limitations described above, certificate-authenticated TLS is considered mandatory by all security guidelines whenever a web site hosts confidential information or performs material transactions.
[src:x509-certificates/public-key-certificate] This is because, in practice, in spite of the weaknesses described above, web sites secured by public-key certificates are still more secure than unsecured http:// web sites.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] In cryptography and computer security, **self-signed certificates** are public key certificates that are not issued by a certificate authority (CA).
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] These self-signed certificates are easy to make and do not cost money.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] However, they do not provide any trust value.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] For instance, if a website owner uses a self-signed certificate to provide HTTPS services, people who visit that website cannot be certain that they are connected to their intended destination.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] For all they know, a malicious third-party could be redirecting the connection using another self-signed certificate bearing the same holder name.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The connection is still encrypted, but does not necessarily lead to its intended target.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] In comparison, a certificate signed by a trusted CA prevents this attack because the user's web browser separately validates the certificate against the issuing CA.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The attacker's certificate fails this validation.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Self-signed certificates can be created for free, using a wide variety of tools including OpenSSL, Java's keytool, Adobe Reader, wolfSSL and Apple's Keychain.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] They are easy to customize; e.g, they can have larger key sizes or hold additional metadata.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Their use doesn't involve the problems of trusting third parties that may improperly sign certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Self-signed certificate transactions usually present a far smaller attack surface by eliminating both the complex certificate chain validation, and certificate revocation checks like CRL and OCSP.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] In a CA-based PKI system, parties engaged in secure communication must trust a CA, i.e. place the CA certificates in a whitelist of trusted certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Developers of web browsers may use procedures specified by the CA/Browser Forum to whitelist well-known, public certificate authorities.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Individual groups and companies may whitelist additional, private CA certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The trust issues of an entity accepting a new self-signed certificate are similar to the issues of an entity trusting the addition of a new CA certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The parties in a self-signed PKI must establish trust with each other (using procedures outside the PKI), and confirm the accurate transfer of public keys e.g. compare the certificate's cryptographic hash out of band.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] There are many subtle differences between CA signed and self-signed certificates, especially in the amount of trust that can be placed in the security assertions of the certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Some CAs can verify the identity of the person to whom they issue a certificate; for example the US military issues their Common Access Cards in person, with multiple forms of other ID.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The CA can attest identity values like these by including them in the signed certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The entity that validates the certificate can trust the information in that certificate, to the same extent that they trust the CA that signed it (and by implication, the security procedures the CA used to verify the attested information).
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] With a self-signed certificate by contrast, trust of the values in the certificate are more complicated because the entity possesses the signing key, and can always generate a new certificate with different values.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] For example, the validity dates of a self-signed certificate might not be trusted because the entity could always create and sign a new certificate that contained a valid date range.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The values in a self-signed certificate can only be trusted when the values were verified out-of-band during the acceptance of the certificate, and there is a method to verify the self-signed certificate has not changed after it was trusted.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] For example, the procedure of trusting a self-signed certificate includes a manual verification of validity dates, and a hash of the certificate is incorporated into the white list.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Special treatment of X.509 certificate fields for self-signed certificate can be found in RFC 3280.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Revocation of self-signed certificates differs from CA-signed certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] By nature, no entity (CA or others) can revoke a self-signed certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] But one could invalidate a self-signed CA by removing it from the trust whitelist.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Self-signed certificates have limited uses, e.g. in the cases where the issuer and the sole user are the same entity.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] For example, the Encrypting File System on Microsoft Windows issues a self-signed certificate on behalf of a user account to transparently encrypt and decrypt files on the fly.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] Another example is a root certificate, which is a form of self-signed certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] The terms "self-signed" and "self-issued" are occasionally used interchangeably and "self-signed certificate" is sometimes even incorrectly used to indicate a certificate issued by a private (not publicly trusted) CA.
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] RFC 5280 defines self-signed certificates as "self-issued certificates where the digital signature may be verified by the public key bound into the certificate", whereas a self-issued certificate is a certificate "in which the issuer and subject are the same entity".
[src:x509-certificates/self-signed-certificate] While in the strict sense the RFC makes this definition only for CA certificates, there is no reason to also adopt that definition for end-entity certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In cryptography, **X.509** is an International Telecommunication Union (ITU) standard defining the format of public key certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] X.509 certificates are used in many Internet protocols, including TLS/SSL, which is the basis for HTTPS, the secure protocol for browsing the web.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] They are also used in offline applications, like electronic signatures.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An X.509 certificate binds an identity to a public key using a digital signature.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A certificate contains an identity (a hostname, or an organization, or an individual) and a public key (RSA, DSA, ECDSA, ed25519, etc.), and is either signed by a certificate authority (CA) or is self-signed.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] When a certificate is signed by a trusted certificate authority, or validated by other means, someone holding that certificate can use the public key it contains to establish secure communications with another party, or validate documents digitally signed by the corresponding private key.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] X.509 is defined by the ITU's "Standardization Sector" (ITU-T's SG17), in ITU-T Study Group 17 and is based on Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1), another ITU-T standard.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] X.509 was initially issued on July 3, 1988, and was begun in association with the X.500 standard.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The first tasks of it was providing users with secure access to information resources and avoiding a cryptographic man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] It assumes a strict hierarchical system of certificate authorities (CAs) for issuing the certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This contrasts with web of trust models, like PGP, where anyone (not just special CAs) may sign and thus attest to the validity of others' key certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Version 3 of X.509 includes the flexibility to support other topologies like bridges and meshes.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] It can be used in a peer-to-peer, OpenPGP-like web of trust, but was rarely used that way as of 2004.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The X.500 system has only been implemented by sovereign nations for state identity information sharing treaty fulfillment purposes, and the IETF's Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509) (PKIX) working group has adapted the standard to the more flexible organization of the Internet.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In fact, the term *X.509 certificate* usually refers to the IETF's PKIX certificate and CRL profile of the X.509 v3 certificate standard, as specified in RFC 5280, commonly called PKIX for *Public Key Infrastructure (X.509)*.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An early issue with Public Key Infrastructure (PKI) and X.509 certificates was the well known "which directory" problem.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The problem is the client does not know where to fetch missing intermediate certificates because the global X.500 directory never materialized.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The problem was mitigated by including all intermediate certificates in a request.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, early web servers only sent the web server's certificate to the client.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Clients that lacked an intermediate CA certificate or where to find them failed to build a valid path from the CA to the server's certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] To work around the problem, web servers now send all the intermediate certificates along with the web server's certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] While PKIX refers to the IETF's or Internet's PKI standard, there are many other PKIs with different policies.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, the US Government has its own PKI with its own policies, and the CA/Browser Forum has its own PKI with its own policies.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The US Government's PKI is a massive book of over 2500 pages.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] If an organization's PKI diverges too much from that of the IETF or CA/Browser Forum, then the organization risks losing interoperability with common tools like web browsers, cURL, and Wget.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, if a PKI has a policy of only issuing certificates on Monday, then common tools like cURL and Wget will not enforce the policy and allow a certificate issued on a Tuesday.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] X.509 certificates bind an identity to a public key using a digital signature.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In the X.509 system, there are two types of certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The second is an end-entity certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A CA certificate can issue other certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The top level, self-signed CA certificate is sometimes called the Root CA certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Other CA certificates are called intermediate CA or subordinate CA certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An end-entity certificate identifies the user, like a person, organization or business.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An end-entity certificate *cannot* issue other certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An end-entity certificate is sometimes called a leaf certificate since no other certificates can be issued below it.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An organization that wants a signed certificate requests one from a CA using a protocol like Certificate Signing Request (CSR), Simple Certificate Enrollment Protocol (SCEP) or Certificate Management Protocol (CMP).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The organization first generates a key pair, keeping the private key secret and using it to sign the CSR.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The CSR contains information identifying the applicant and the applicant's public key that is used to verify the signature of the CSR - and the Distinguished Name (DN) that is unique for the person, organization or business.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The CSR may be accompanied by other credentials or proofs of identity required by the certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The CSR will be validated using a Registration Authority (RA), and then the certification authority will issue a certificate binding a public key to a particular distinguished name.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The roles registration authority and certification authority are usually separate business units under separation of duties to reduce the risk of fraud.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An organization's trusted root certificates can be distributed to all employees so that they can use the company PKI system.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, Firefox provides a CSV and/or HTML file containing a list of Included CAs.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] X.509 and RFC 5280 also include standards for certificate revocation list (CRL) implementations.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Another IETF-approved way of checking a certificate's validity is the Online Certificate Status Protocol (OCSP).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Firefox 3.0 enabled OCSP checking by default, as did versions of Windows from at least Vista and later.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The structure foreseen by the standards is expressed in a formal language, Abstract Syntax Notation One (ASN.1).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The Extensions field, if present, is a sequence of one or more certificate extensions.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Each extension has its own unique ID, expressed as object identifier (OID), which is a set of values, together with either a critical or non-critical indication.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A certificate-using system must reject the certificate if it encounters a critical extension that it does not recognize, or a critical extension that contains information that it cannot process.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A non-critical extension may be ignored if it is not recognized, but must be processed if it is recognized.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The structure of version 1 is given in RFC 1422.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The inner format of issuer and subject unique identifiers specified in *X.520 The Directory: Selected attribute types* recommendation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] ITU-T introduced issuer and subject unique identifiers in version 2 to permit the reuse of issuer or subject name after some time.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An example of reuse will be when a CA goes bankrupt and its name is deleted from the country's public list.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] After some time another CA with the same name may register itself, even though it is unrelated to the first one.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] However, IETF recommends that no issuer and subject names be reused.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Therefore, version 2 is not widely deployed in the Internet.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Extensions were introduced in version 3.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A CA can use extensions to issue a certificate only for a specific purpose (e.g. only for signing digital objects).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In all versions, the serial number must be unique for each certificate issued by a specific CA (as mentioned in RFC 5280).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] RFC 5280 (and its predecessors) defines a number of certificate extensions which indicate how the certificate should be used.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Most of them are arcs from the `joint-iso-ccitt(2) ds(5) id-ce(29)` OID.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In general when using RFC 5280, if a certificate has several extensions restricting its use, all restrictions must be satisfied for a given use to be appropriate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The RFC gives the specific example of a certificate containing both keyUsage and extendedKeyUsage: in this case, both must be processed and the certificate can only be used if both extensions are coherent in specifying the usage of a certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, NSS uses both extensions to specify certificate usage.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Certification authorities operating under the CA/Browser Forum's PKI issue certificates with varying levels of validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The different validations provide different levels of assurances that a certificate represents what it is supposed to.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] For example, a web server can be validated at the lowest level of assurances using an email called *Domain Validation (DV)*.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Or a web server can be validated at a higher level of assurances using more detailed methods called *Extended Validation (EV)*.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In practice, a DV certificate means a certificate was issued for a domain like `example.com` after control over that domain was asserted, e.g. by responding to an email sent to `webmaster@example.com`.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] An EV certificate means a certificate was issued for a domain like `example.com`, and a company like Example, LLC is the owner of the domain, and the owner was verified by Articles of Incorporation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Extended validation does not add any additional security controls, so the secure channel setup using an EV certificate is not "stronger" than a channel setup using a different level of validation like DV.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Extended validation is signaled in a certificate using X.509 v3 extension.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Each CA uses a different Object Identifier (OID) to assert extended validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] There is no single OID to indicate extended validation, which complicates user agent programming.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Each user agent must have a list of OIDs that indicate extended validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The CA/Browser Forum's PKI recognizes extended validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Other PKIs, like the Internet's PKI (PKIX), do not place any special emphasis on extended validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Tools using PKIX policies, like cURL and Wget, simply treat an EV certificate like any other certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Until 2019, many browsers used to provide strong visual feedback in the URL bar to the user to indicate a site provides an EV certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Following studies and reports that showed the ineffectiveness of EV certificates and their utility to criminals for injecting misleading elements into the central part of the browser's UI, all major browsers removed their previous prominent visual feedback from the URL bar.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Instead, since 2019, browsers such as Chromium and Firefox hide the EV issued-to information in sub-menus, where it is displayed in a neutral way, without any highlighting or mentioning of extended validation.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Security expert Peter Gutmann states CA's created EV certificates to restore profit levels after the Race to the Bottom cut into profits.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] During the race to the bottom CA's cut prices to lure consumers to purchase their certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] As a result, profits were reduced and CA's dropped the level of validation they were performing to the point there were nearly no assurances on a certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] There are several commonly used filename extensions for X.509 certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Some of these extensions are also used for other data such as private keys.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] PKCS#7 is a standard for signing or encrypting (officially called "enveloping") data.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Since the certificate is needed to verify signed data, it is possible to include them in the SignedData structure.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Each certificate (except the last one) is signed by the secret key corresponding to the next certificate in the chain (i.e. the signature of one certificate can be verified using the public key contained in the following certificate).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The last certificate in the list is a trust anchor: a certificate that you trust because it was delivered to you by some trustworthy procedure.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Certificate chains are used in order to check that the public key (PK) contained in a target certificate (the first certificate in the chain) and other data contained in it effectively belongs to its subject.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In order to ascertain this, the signature on the target certificate is verified by using the PK contained in the following certificate, whose signature is verified using the next certificate, and so on until the last certificate in the chain is reached.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] As the last certificate is a trust anchor, successfully reaching it will prove that the target certificate can be trusted.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The description in the preceding paragraph is a simplified view on the certification path validation process, which involves additional checks, such as verifying validity dates on certificates, looking up CRLs, etc.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] A concrete certificate can be part of very different certificate chains (all of them valid).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This is because several CA certificates can be generated for the same subject and public key, but be signed with different private keys (from different CAs or different private keys from the same CA).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] So, although a single X.509 certificate can have only one issuer and one CA signature, it can be validly linked to more than one certificate, building completely different certificate chains.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This is crucial for cross-certification between PKIs and other applications.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In order to manage that user certificates existing in PKI 2 (like "User 2") are trusted by PKI 1, CA1 generates a certificate (cert2.1) containing the public key of CA2.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Now both "cert2 and cert2.1 (in green) have the same subject and public key, so there are two valid chains for cert2.2 (User 2): "cert2.2 → cert2" and "cert2.2 → cert2.1 → cert1".
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Similarly, CA2 can generate a certificate (cert1.1) containing the public key of CA1 so that user certificates existing in PKI 1 (like "User 1") are trusted by PKI 2.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Since both cert1 and cert3 contain the same public key (the old one), there are two valid certificate chains for cert5: "cert5 → cert1" and "cert5 → cert3 → cert2", and analogously for cert6.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This allows that old user certificates (such as cert5) and new certificates (such as cert6) can be trusted indifferently by a party having either the new root CA certificate or the old one as trust anchor during the transition to the new CA keys.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This is an example of a decoded X.509 certificate that was used in the past by wikipedia.org and several other Wikipedia websites.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] It was issued by GlobalSign, as stated in the Issuer field.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Its Subject field describes Wikipedia as an organization, and its Subject Alternative Name (SAN) field for DNS describes the hostnames for which it could be used.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The Subject Public Key Info field contains an ECDSA public key, while the signature at the bottom was generated by GlobalSign's RSA private key.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In a TLS connection, a properly-configured server would provide the intermediate as part of the handshake.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] However, it's also possible to retrieve the intermediate certificate by fetching the "CA Issuers" URL from the end-entity certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This is an example of an intermediate certificate belonging to a certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This certificate signed the end-entity certificate above, and was signed by the root certificate below.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Note that the subject field of this intermediate certificate matches the issuer field of the end-entity certificate that it signed.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Also, the "subject key identifier" field in the intermediate matches the "authority key identifier" field in the end-entity certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This is an example of a self-signed root certificate representing a certificate authority.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Its issuer and subject fields are the same, and its signature can be validated with its own public key.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Validation of the trust chain has to end here.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] If the validating program has this root certificate in its trust store, the end-entity certificate can be considered trusted for use in a TLS connection.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Otherwise, the end-entity certificate is considered untrusted.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] There are a number of publications about PKI problems by Bruce Schneier, Peter Gutmann and other security experts.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Implementations suffer from design flaws, bugs, different interpretations of standards and lack of interoperability of different standards.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Digital signature systems depend on secure cryptographic hash functions to work.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] When a public key infrastructure allows the use of a hash function that is no longer secure, an attacker can exploit weaknesses in the hash function to forge certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Specifically, if an attacker is able to produce a hash collision, they can convince a CA to sign a certificate with innocuous contents, where the hash of those contents is identical to the hash of another, malicious set of certificate contents, created by the attacker with values of their choosing.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The attacker can then append the CA-provided signature to their malicious certificate contents, resulting in a malicious certificate that appears to be signed by the CA.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Because the malicious certificate contents are chosen solely by the attacker, they can have different validity dates or hostnames than the innocuous certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The malicious certificate can even contain a "CA: true" field making it able to issue further trusted certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Exploiting a hash collision to forge X.509 signatures requires that the attacker be able to predict the data that the certificate authority will sign.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] This can be somewhat mitigated by the CA generating a random component in the certificates it signs, typically the serial number.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The CA/Browser Forum has required serial number entropy in its Baseline Requirements Section 7.1 since 2011.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] As of January 1, 2016, the Baseline Requirements forbid issuance of certificates using SHA-1.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] As of early 2017, Chrome and Firefox reject certificates that use SHA-1.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] As of May 2017 both Edge and Safari are also rejecting SHA-1 certificate.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] OpenSSL began rejecting SHA-1 certificates by default in version 3.0, released September 2021.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In 1995, the Internet Engineering Task Force in conjunction with the National Institute of Standards and Technology formed the Public-Key Infrastructure (X.509) working group.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The working group, concluded in June 2014, is commonly referred to as "PKIX." It produced RFCs and other standards documentation on using and deploying X.509 in practice.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] In particular it produced RFC 3280 and its successor RFC 5280, which define how to use X.509 in Internet protocols.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] TLS/SSL and HTTPS use the RFC 5280 profile of X.509, as do S/MIME (Secure Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) and the EAP-TLS method for WiFi authentication.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Any protocol that uses TLS, such as SMTP, POP, IMAP, LDAP, XMPP, and many more, inherently uses X.509.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] IPsec can use the RFC 4945 profile for authenticating peers.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The OpenCable security specification defines its own profile of X.509 for use in the cable industry.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Devices like smart cards and TPMs often carry certificates to identify themselves or their owners.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The WS-Security standard defines authentication either through TLS or through its own certificate profile.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The Microsoft Authenticode code signing system uses X.509 to identify authors of computer programs.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] Secure Boot feature of UEFI uses X.509 to authenticate UEFI drivers or bootloaders during booting and disallow blocklisted drivers or bootloaders (by using Forbidden Key Exchange or dbx database).
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] The OPC UA industrial automation communication standard uses X.509.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] SSH generally uses a Trust On First Use security model and doesn't have need for certificates.
[src:x509-certificates/x-509] However, the popular OpenSSH implementation does support a CA-signed identity model based on its own non-X.509 certificate format.
